The best approach for `File.*` and `Directory.*` is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already provides `IFileSystem` with mock support.

### 1. Install the packages

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs or Startup.cs:
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers;

var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
// MockFileSystem automatically includes its directories,
// so Directory.Exists("/data") returns true.

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/data/config.json"));

manager.Save("/data/out.json", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/out.json"));

Assert.True(manager.EnsureDirectory("/data"));
Assert.False(manager.EnsureDirectory("/missing"));
```

### Why this over a custom wrapper?

| | Custom `IFileSystem` | `System.IO.Abstractions` |
|---|---|---|
| Coverage | Only what you wrap | Full `System.IO` surface |
| Maintenance | You own it | Community-maintained |
| Test helpers | You build them | `MockFileSystem` included |
| Risk of bugs | Higher | Battle-tested |

**TL;DR** — Install `System.IO.Abstractions`, register `IFileSystem` as a singleton, inject it everywhere you use `File.*` or `Directory.*`, and use `MockFileSystem` in tests. No custom wrapper code needed.
